44:50.221 --> 44:57.528 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And it was crazy. I thought not
seeing emotion
was disabling, but seeing it in
such tremendous

44:57.562 --> 45:03.901 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
intensity was, frankly, really
disabling and,
of course, thankfully, it
moderated.

45:03.935 --> 45:08.306 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: But what did
you see? Did
you have an expectation that
there was a world

45:08.339 --> 45:11.676 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of joy and happiness that you
weren't plugging
into?

45:11.709 --> 45:16.414 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN ELDER ROBISON: I did. And I
was just
a -- I was just a crazy fool for
that, because

45:16.447 --> 45:21.018 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
anyone who looks at the news
knows that the
world is not beauty and joy and
light.

45:21.052 --> 45:25.022 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Well, I thought those are the
messages I'm
missing, and if I could get
them, I would

45:25.056 --> 45:31.095 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
be happy. And instead, the
messages were angst,
and jealousy and fear and worry
and...

45:31.128 --> 45:33.230 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: This is what
people around
you were exhibiting?

45:33.264 --> 45:37.301 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOHN ELDER ROBISON: It was a
pretty big shock
to me.

45:37.335 --> 45:43.708 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And the thing that was maybe the
hardest was
seeing people looking at me,
sometimes with

45:43.741 --> 45:51.182 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
contempt or derision. And even
my memories,
for me to remember a time when I
was laughing

45:51.215 --> 45:56.621 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
with somebody, and after the
enlightenment
of the TMS, I realized they were
laughing

45:56.654 --> 45:59.724 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
at me. And that made me really,
really sad.

45:59.757 --> 46:03.628 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: This also cost
you the relationship
at home with your wife.

46:03.661 --> 46:11.836 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN ELDER ROBISON: It cost me
my marriage.
It cost me clients at work, who
I felt were

46:11.869 --> 46:17.441 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
-- didn't like me. And, of
course, it's a
business, right? And should I
even care if

46:17.475 --> 46:19.543 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
somebody likes me? But I did.

46:19.577 --> 46:26.617 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And it cost me friends. And,
like I said,
it cost me even my memories.

46:26.651 --> 46:30.388 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Now, you go
out of your
way in the book to mention that
this is the

46:30.421 --> 46:34.291 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
experiences that you had, that
even other
people that participated in the
research had

46:34.325 --> 46:38.496 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
very different experiences.
You're not advocating
automatically that this is a
cure for autism

46:38.529 --> 46:39.363 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
or anything like that.

46:39.397 --> 46:41.198 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
JOHN ELDER ROBISON: Oh,
absolutely not.

46:41.232 --> 46:47.571 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This is -- this is not a cure
for autism.
But what it is, is, it's a story
of a powerful

46:47.605 --> 46:52.576 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
transformative experience that
ultimately
had a very positive effect on
me, but it was

46:52.610 --> 46:59.950 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a rough ride. It shows, though,
the tremendous
power of this TMS technology
that's basically

46:59.984 --> 47:04.722 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
unknown. Even as it's
FDA-approved to treat
depression, nobody knows it.

47:04.755 --> 47:09.460 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: You know, this
also makes
me think, looking forward, is
there an era

47:09.493 --> 47:14.532 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that you see where people say,
well, I want
to do something to my brain to
perhaps enhance

47:14.565 --> 47:18.602 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and wake up certain parts of my
brain that
might not be as active or
efficient as they

47:18.636 --> 47:20.271 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
could be?

47:20.304 --> 47:23.908 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN ELDER ROBISON: I think that
that's a
very real thing that we need to
start the

47:23.941 --> 47:25.710 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
conversation about now.

47:25.743 --> 47:31.749 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And that's actually one reason I
wrote "Switched
On," because I'm concerned that
people are

47:31.782 --> 47:37.088 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
going to read my story, which,
frankly, is
like a stepping up of my
emotional intelligence,

47:37.121 --> 47:39.724 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and they're going to read some
of the other
accounts in newspapers, and
they're going

47:39.757 --> 47:43.894 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to think, I'm going to do this
to get my mathematical
I.Q. hopped up.

47:43.928 --> 47:48.866 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And if it's you or me, if we're
intelligent
adults, we can go into it with
our eyes open.

47:48.899 --> 47:52.870 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But what if people start saying,
I'm going
to do this to my child to speed
him up in

47:52.903 --> 48:00.144 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
school? I think we have some
real serious
ethical crises coming with this
kind of technology

48:00.177 --> 48:01.445 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
and how it's going to be used.

48:01.479 --> 48:03.848 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: All right, the
book is called
"Switched On."

48:03.881 --> 48:10.821 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
John Elder Robison, thanks so
much for joining
us.

48:10.855 --> 48:15.593 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JOHN ELDER ROBISON: Thank you.

48:15.626 --> 48:22.733 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Finally, with
growing concern
over concussions and related
injuries, a start-up

48:22.767 --> 48:28.072 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
company in Upstate New York is
using wearable
technology to help keep athletes
safer.

48:28.105 --> 48:33.811 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It is a device that sends head
injury alerts
as soon as they happen on the
field and in

48:33.844 --> 48:38.616 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the ring and also measures the
cumulative
effect of multiple hits.

48:38.649 --> 48:45.289 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
From member station WXXI and
Public Media's
Innovation Trail, Sasha-Ann
Simons WXXI.

48:45.322 --> 48:53.664 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MICHAEL ROBERTSON, Student: We
start off with
a 10-minute run. After the run,
we do what's

48:53.697 --> 49:01.972 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
called a set. We do jumping
jacks, pushups,
squats, like all that kind of
stuff. And we

49:02.006 --> 49:03.774 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
wrap our hands.

49:03.808 --> 49:07.678 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SASHA-ANN SIMONS: It's a daily
ritual for
Michael Robertson. The
16-year-old is on the

49:07.711 --> 49:13.150 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
high school boxing team at
Aquinas Institute.
Six days a week, he gears up to
get in the

49:13.184 --> 49:15.052 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
ring.

49:15.085 --> 49:21.525 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
His head gear is high-tech.
Before every match,
he slips a small sensor inside
his headband

49:21.559 --> 49:32.403 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and then puts a helmet on. Jab
after jab,
the sensor, this one called the
LINX Impact

49:32.436 --> 49:39.510 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Assessment System, or IAS, sends
real-time
data to his coach and parents
through an app.

49:39.543 --> 49:44.348 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Not only does the sensor help
spot signs of
a concussion. It also can
uncover other, more

49:44.381 --> 49:46.250 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
common types of brain injuries.

49:46.283 --> 49:49.587 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DOMINIC ARIOLI, Boxing Coach:
One of the things
that I look at with the device
is not only

49:49.620 --> 49:55.492 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
how hard they're getting hit,
but if they're
getting hit, getting hit how
often with blows

49:55.526 --> 49:57.361 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
that register.

49:57.394 --> 50:01.098 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SASHA-ANN SIMONS: Aquinas has
been field testing
the concussion sensor for about
two years.

50:01.131 --> 50:05.202 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Inside the helmet, the sensor
registers the
amount of force from a blow and
will trigger

50:05.236 --> 50:11.442 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a green, yellow, or red light,
with red being
the indicator that the hit was
too hard to

50:11.475 --> 50:16.413 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ignore. The data's available in
real time
and can be stored for review
after the match.

50:16.447 --> 50:21.652 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DOMINIC ARIOLI: We will check
with the system,
and we will also check with the
student, how

50:21.685 --> 50:24.588 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
did their blow feel? And they're
a pretty
good system.

50:24.622 --> 50:30.628 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
SASHA-ANN SIMONS: The blow is
also given an
impact assessment score.

50:30.661 --> 50:36.233 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID BORKHOLDER, BlackBox
Biometrics: That
gives a number from one to 100,
and so you

50:36.267 --> 50:42.706 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
can -- the individual can gauge
the severity
of each of those impacts on that
scale. But

50:42.740 --> 50:46.010 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
we also capture all the detailed
data, which
is really critical for research.

50:46.043 --> 50:50.681 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
SASHA-ANN SIMONS: David
Borkholder is in charge
of the technology at BlackBox
Biometrics,

50:50.714 --> 50:56.053 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
which created LINX IAS. His team
is brainstorming
ways to push the technology
forward.

50:56.086 --> 51:00.224 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID BORKHOLDER: Another
emerging area that
I think is actually going to be
even more

51:00.257 --> 51:03.961 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
important are repetitive
subconcussive hits.

51:03.994 --> 51:09.233 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
SASHA-ANN SIMONS: Recent
research has shown
that many brain injuries are
from subconcussive

51:09.266 --> 51:13.704 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
